<br>
The problem as Nynnia says is post-188, when fine plate tops out.  At that point you pretty these paths to 250, with some sidelines for part of the way:<br>
<br>
- If you have money to burn - and I mean in the 100K range - you can try the blessed sickles for the POTC/Solstice earring quest.  These trivial over 250.<br>
<br>
- Or, if you have money to burn, you can make the &quot;blue diamond&quot; cultural armor for your race.  Again, we're talking about money in the 100K range.  On the plus side, some of this stuff sells pretty well.  These all trivial at somewhere over 250.<br>
<br>
- In theory, with tons of cash and/or the ability to farm the planes you could try the various planar armors like nightterror steel, but these really aren't viable due to the scarcity of the drops.<br>
<br>
- Some races have viable cultural smithing routes up into the high 200s.  Humans are best off, with imbued field plate going up to 242 or so and a fairly easy-to-farm-for temper (sea temper).  Still expensive, but you can farm your padding &amp; temper components to save cash.  Total costs will still be in the tens of thousands of PP.<br>
<br>
- You can do shadowscream steel.  I don't know much about this personally but there is a wealth of information about it at EQ Traders.  Vastly cheaper than the others with costs of a few thousand plat as I understand it (if you farm all your components) but a significant time sink.<br>
<br>
Along the way the new LDoN armors cover part of the path.  These aren't too expensive to make if you can find the temper components and actually seem to sell decently; they're nice armor with no level restrictions.  The plate BPs seem to trivial at about 212.<br>
<br>
Some general advice from someone who's been blacksmithing for almost 3 years (blacksmithing 178 as Amerygn, 204 on an alt):<br>
<br>
- Get a set of tradeskilling gear that will boost either your WIS or INT to the highest level you can, preferably over 200.  The higher of these two stats affects your chances for a skill-up, and believe me the difference between 175 INT and 200 are noticeable.  KEI or similar mind buffs are a must too.  Trust me, investing in this now will save you both time and money along the way.<br>
<br>
- For leather padding, farm in Marus Seru for LQ hopper hides (use the regular greyhopper hides to boost your tailoring cheaply while you're at it) and gather your spiderling silks in Feerrott.  As a bard I can gather enough silks for 100 paddings in about an hour; takes about 2-3 hours for that many hides.  YMMV.<br>
<br>
- Invest in a geerlock smithing hammer.  There's some strong statistical evidence that there's a relationship between a successful combine and your chance for a skill-up, and a geerlock will give you a higher apparent level where chances of success are concerned.<br>
<br>
- For the same reason, try not to attempt combines which have trivial levels very high above your current skill.  If nothing else, you'll minimize your losses - since you lose money even on successful combines, reducing failed combines is a big part of skilling up.<br>
<br>
- Plan for 1 skillup per 40 combines at the higher levels on average.  With higher INT or WIS (as in 225+) you can get this to about 1 in 25 or so.  Either way, you WILL go through stretches of 100+ combines without a skill up.  It's heartbreaking but every smith goes through those.  <br>
<br>
Hope this helps, and welcome to the insanity that is blacksmithing in EQ!<br>
